Make the memory-pressure purge threshold and poll interval tunable.

Device-measured root cause of the "big lag spikes" while scrolling heavy,
image/video-rich feeds (reddit): the spikes are kernel memory-pressure
thrashing, not rendering. As the page grows, the WebProcess RSS climbs to
~700 MB; on this 3.5 GB device the rest of RAM is already held by
lipstick/system, so at that footprint the kernel lowmemorykiller starts
reaping processes and the WebProcess's own pages get evicted and faulted back
in (measured ~1700 major faults in a 10 s scroll). Each major fault blocks the
main thread, producing multi-second frames.

WebKit has a MemoryPressureHandler that would release its decoded-image / page
/ tile caches under pressure (releaseMemory), which keeps RSS bounded - exactly
what is needed - but its defaults never fire in time here:
  baseThreshold      = min(3 GB, ramSize())  -> 3 GB
  conservative purge = baseThreshold * 0.33  -> ~1 GB footprint
  strict purge       = baseThreshold * 0.5   -> ~1.5 GB footprint
  pollInterval       = 30 s
So WebKit only starts purging at ~1 GB and re-checks every 30 s, while the
system already thrashes at ~700 MB. WebKit never feels pressure before the
kernel does, so it never releases its caches.

Make the default configuration honour two env vars so the device can set a
realistic budget (the kill threshold is unaffected - it is derived from
ramSize(), not baseThreshold, so this only changes WHEN caches are purged, not
when the process is killed):
  WEBKIT_MEMORY_BASE_THRESHOLD_MB  - baseThreshold in MB (default min(3 GB, RAM))
  WEBKIT_MEMORY_POLL_INTERVAL_MS   - footprint poll interval in ms (default 30000)
deploy/runtime-common.sh exports the device defaults (1200 MB base => purge
starts at ~400 MB / strict at ~600 MB; 3 s poll). Defaults are unchanged when
the env vars are unset, so light pages (footprint < ~400 MB) see no change.
--- a/Source/WTF/wtf/MemoryPressureHandler.cpp
+++ b/Source/WTF/wtf/MemoryPressureHandler.cpp
@@ -29,5 +29,6 @@
 #include <algorithm>
 #include <atomic>
+#include <cstdlib>
 #include <functional>
 #include <ranges>
 #include <wtf/Logging.h>
@@ -372,4 +373,24 @@
     , killThresholdFraction(s_killThresholdFraction)
     , pollInterval(s_pollInterval)
 {
+    // Atlantic: on a memory-constrained device (3.5 GB, most of it held by
+    // lipstick/system) the upstream defaults purge caches far too late - only at
+    // ~1 GB footprint (conservative) / ~1.5 GB (strict), re-checked every 30 s -
+    // while the WebProcess footprint that actually drives the SYSTEM into the
+    // kernel lowmemorykiller (and multi-second major-fault thrashing during
+    // scroll) is only ~700 MB. WebKit therefore never releases its
+    // decoded-image / page / tile caches before the kernel starts reaping. Allow
+    // the device to set a realistic budget so the handler purges early and often.
+    // Only the purge thresholds move; the kill threshold is derived from
+    // ramSize(), not baseThreshold, so the process is not killed any earlier.
+    // Defaults are unchanged when the env vars are unset. See
+    // webkit-memory-pressure-threshold-env.patch.
+    if (const char* baseMB = getenv("WEBKIT_MEMORY_BASE_THRESHOLD_MB")) {
+        if (long mb = atol(baseMB); mb > 0)
+            baseThreshold = static_cast<uint64_t>(mb) * MB;
+    }
+    if (const char* intervalMS = getenv("WEBKIT_MEMORY_POLL_INTERVAL_MS")) {
+        if (long ms = atol(intervalMS); ms > 0)
+            pollInterval = Seconds::fromMilliseconds(ms);
+    }
 }
